
[1]ingratiate

   INGRA'TIATE, v.t. ingra'shate. [L. in and gratia, favor.]

   1. To commend one's self to another's good will, confidence or
   kindness. It is always used as a reciprocal verb,and followed by with,
   before the person whose favor is sought. Ministers and courtiers
   ingratiate themselves with their sovereign. Demagogues ingratiate
   themselves with the populace.

   2. To recommend; to render easy; used of things.
